The government wants to stop the torture of "witches" and issued a brochure
Women who are labelled as witches in Burkina Faso usually have some common social characteristics.
They belong more to the older generation, they cannot find work - for health reasons, for example, they are single and have no children.
When one of these women becomes a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
"Men are rarely affected by this fate."
"Even young and healthy women are spared this, as they help with the work and give birth to children," says a nun, describing the situation in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, where more than a hundred women are taken care of in a special home, which has been expelled by their communities.
The local government decided now to proceed against this abnormal "social measure".
For this reason, he issued a pamphlet to stop the "witch hunt".
But there is a catch.
"More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," the newspaper "derStandard" pointed out the dilemma of written enlightenment.
But to be accused of witchcraft is also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, the 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they doused her with kerosene and simply set her on fire.
The BBC also reported on this incident.
The perpetrators claimed, however, that the matter was only a coincidence of unfortunate circumstances.
According to her version, oil used for ritual anointings was inflamed.
This happened after the group had tried to "drive an evil spirit" out of the woman.
People here support the isolation of "witches" regardless of their education.
"Der Standard" quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: "Female eaters of human souls are a danger both in the past and today", he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, last year the Gambian president himself played a significant role.
"After the death of his aunt, President Yahya Jammeh started a monstrous witch hunt, as they allegedly had a share in their deaths and would now try to kill the president himself by black magic."
"He called for the help of shamans from nearby Guinea who, accompanied by policemen, soldiers and the President's personal guard, forcibly abducted women and men from Gambian villages and brought them to the President's farm in Kanilai," the organization Amnesty International stated in its report.
On the farm, incarcerated people were forced to drink a brew of hallucinogenic plants, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive the stay on the farm.
It was only due to international pressure that the nearly one thousand prisoners were released.
A tenant of Bakala: He heats in the stove - nevertheless pays higher rent
An elderly squatted man is leaving the client centre of the company RPG Byty of the "Coal Baron" Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rented apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm, a portfolio of three new rental contracts for three apartments: his own and the apartments of his daughters and his son, who is serving a prison sentence.
In the context of the so-called "deregulation", the rent was increased for all three.
Instead of 3500 crowns per month, the son is to pay 4100 crowns next year for a 2 room apartment with kitchen of the second category.
"And there's not even running hot water in the apartment and you have to heat it in a simple coal stove," he angrily taps at the son's new lease, which he has the power to sign.
"But what - I signed it", he explains half disgruntled and half resigned.
The citizens' association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new lease conditions as "incorrect and immoral", advises tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, when they will publish instructions on how to proceed against such contracts.
But the man only waves away.
"One says this, the other says that," he makes a dark face.
The Ostrava region thus becomes a large "deregulation laboratory".
After the New Year, this deregulation is imminent for most rental apartments in the Czech Republic, whose tenants have not yet paid a market-oriented rent.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit this "laboratory" personally.
The RPG ’ s waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full at nine o ’ clock in the morning this Tuesday.
Right next to the door are the bodyguards of a security agency and a calling device.
"Rent 2011", that's how a special keypad lights up on the touchscreen.
Just touch the button and the device spits out a number slip.
Hardly have we deciphered the number "157" and it beeps on the large display on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later, it is your turn.
A little later, an elderly couple enters the waiting room to ask for the rent, but the rush in the waiting room does not seem to apply to the new rent at all.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair requests, insurance matters and the like.
Starting in mid-November, the envelopes with the new leases in the Ostrava region will flutter into the mailboxes of most of the tenants of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
The RPG Byty suggests to them in the letters a rent increase of approx. 15 to 38 per cent.
The special counter for new rentals in the Client Centre has been open since 18 November.
"The action runs a little over a week, that is, it's just the beginning," the ladies behind the counter answer after a moment's hesitation when the "client" turns out to be a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala ’ s former miners ’ homes are a hot topic.
Before the elections, Ostrava-based parliamentary vice-president Lubomír Zaorálek from the ČSSD raised this issue quite loudly, no wonder that newspapers are full of it today.
"Twenty years I want a new floor from them."
"Not even a damp. Toilet glasses they could replace", makes the man mentioned at the beginning air.
So far, according to the staff, it is mainly pensioners who stand at the counter to see if they really get the promised rent reduction that RPG promises if they sign the special offer in time.
The other tenants who sign the new lease by December 15 will also benefit from a half-reduced February lease.
So far, however, "deregulation switch" in Havířov is anything but overloaded with demands.
"Of yesterday's 360 clients only about 40 to 50 of the rent in 2011 were here because of", estimate the counter officials.
RPG offers individual rental agreements, where necessary, both on its websites and on blackboards.
However, if the tenants do not agree on the new rent, it will be determined by an independent court.
"This is not intended as a threat, but as information about the only possible and fully legitimate legal procedure," RPG explains on its websites.
"Nobody goes to court here," says one of the RPG Byty employees, and a man on the street in front of the client center at least partially agrees.
"I have a pension of 13,000 (crowns), of which 5,000 are left over for food, where should I get the money for a lawsuit," he says.
Then the employee becomes insecure.
"Let's see."
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them through the media not to sign, so people are still waiting," she says.
The regulated rent ends in most of the Czech Republic by New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty the rent increase is an economic necessity.
"The existing level of rents is not even sufficient to maintain the housing fund," argues Pavel Klimeš, director of the housing portfolio of the company RPG Byty and - especially the neglect of the housing fund criticised by the angry tenants is, in the opinion of the homeowners, the main reason for the rent increase.
Whereas in the years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion Euros from the income rents in the apartments, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it is supposed to be 5.2 billion.
On the large-format LCD display on the ceiling opposite the upholstered armchairs in the waiting room of Havířov, a few red shining information appear again and again in between.
"The rent increases in 2011 of 15% and less affect 31 200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of the apartments of RPG."
"Always this means a maximum of 7.50 CZK per square meter and month," says the LCD monitor.
Rent increases by 38 percent for only 400 apartments from RPG ’ s portfolio.
"In these cases, it is about increasing extremely low rental rates of 19.66 CZK per square meter," argues RPG.
With 2600 apartments, the rent remains the same next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not drive up rents by leaps and bounds, but will take place gradually within four and eight years.
What's more - the company imposes a further obligation: All income from the rent increase (see diagram) the company wants to put back into the apartments, especially in heat savings - in new windows and in the thermal insulation.
But - first and foremost these should benefit those people who sign the agreements about the rent increase.
The architects agreed - the office also includes a kindergarten
The office building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colourful walls, creative furniture, a lot of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design staff since last year.
The design and architectural office Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of well-known buildings in Brno originate, calculated from the first drafts for the new building Avriopoint the premises for its company, the Minikindergarten.
In wise foresight, because most of its 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is keen that the designers and architects return to their jobs as soon as possible.
Together with the possibility to work shorter hours, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for civil engineers and architects to reconcile their demanding profession with caring for children.
The Minikindergarten is an original idea of the staff of Arch.Design and with the support of the management they succeeded in winning funds from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs for their project.
The mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment Policy from the resources of the European Social Fund and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (grants of CZK 2.8 million), it was possible to obtain the necessary facilities and equipment, and for a period of two years, qualified personnel and operations were provided.
After the use of the subsidies (2 years) the company Arch.Design is obliged to continue running the mini kindergarten for 3 more years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took an entire year, with the company Economy Rating providing active assistance in the application process.
The children are looked after by qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher, and children can attend the kindergarten without age restrictions, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini kindergarten, may be present at the same time only 5 Children, However, the day over several children alternate with each other.
The kindergarten is flexibly adapted to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights with regard to the use of the kindergarten - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini kindergarten is still comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
The children do not only play here, but above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, besides they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer at the disposal of the children.
What's more - the presence of young children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive corporate environment.
Parents can take a look at the children at any time and so the stress of late collection of the children from a far away kindergarten is eliminated.
Parents therefore use their working time more productively.
No wonder natural and loyal employers, too, are forming relationships.
In this way Arch.Design ranks among the Czech companies that offer significant benefits in the recruitment of new employees, are family-friendly and strengthen their personnel marketing with such programs.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
The house with its organic forms got the nickname "bone house" from the local inhabitants.
Organic shapes, wild colours, the unusual use of stone, tile splinters and mosaics, the scale-like façades and the ubiquitous soft lines are all typical features of Art Nouveau by Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with dreamlike lines, tender colors and textures, which remind of nature and living beings.
Only on closer inspection do you notice that everything is governed by geometry, rhythm and thoughtful order.
At night, the entire façade appears even more sculptural, dramatic and the special illumination intensifies the brilliance of the colours.
The same sweeping lines and intricate shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wavy wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and mouldings.
The Batlló House is located in the Eixample district, on the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, 43, and was created by the renovation of a house built in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old building and the construction of a completely new one, but in the end he agreed with Gaudí ’ s idea for an unusual and also cheaper reconstruction.
But Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló alone.
He collaborated with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his drawing board that the decorations for the representative apartment of the reality owner were created, and the use of mosaics on the façade was his idea.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol was also involved in the construction of Gaudí ’ s Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also contains other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion the house got the nickname "bone house" from the local inhabitants of its organic forms.
Others called it the "yawning house" because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house with ventilation ducts and typical fireplaces.
Their 45 degrees inclination seems a bit bizarre.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations of the time and was by no means misled by them.
Prior to the commencement of construction, he obtained the corresponding building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, when it was completed, the city fathers were so appalled by the result that they demanded remedy.
The councillors also stumbled upon the fact that the building with its pillars even interfered with the public sidewalk.
However, there were no changes, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the request of the district, Josep Batlló applied for permission to let the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a parlour, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey building passes through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reconstruction eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger company could chat comfortably without having to renounce a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
Due to Gaudí's reconstruction, the house received not only a new façade but also a rather unusual roof and two further floors.
Gaudí ’ s play with light is also impressive, as are the blue and white glazed tiles that cover the courtyard and the atria.
The play of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
In doing so, he simply made use of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colours, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
The Casa Batlló, listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The owners of the house decided to take this step only in the year, on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was discovered that this was a very profitable business, the visits were maintained and even extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price for visiting the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the house inhabitants and visit him at home.
The right mattress and bed rust? Women have other wishes than men
Not the best bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface - so mattress and rust make up the good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to meet the wishes of the specific user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, the height, the state of health and last but not least also the sex of the sleeper.
Just as important is the interior, in which mattress and rust have to be subordinated.
Typical example?
In a weekend house, where there is no regular heating, latex mattresses are not suitable, as they take much longer to "warm up".
In addition, they are significantly heavier than standard polyurethane ， mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
If they do not have enough ventilation tubes in the core and, moreover, lie on a solid plate, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not impossible that mould forms under them.
