More and more parents want people to have surveillance equipment to keep the kids under control
Fear for their own children is growing, and more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system that was originally invented to search for cars is just as capable of locating people, which would also be helpful in such cases, as recently with the disappearance without a trace of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a cigarette pack, but soon it will be no bigger than a wristwatch.
Many people have been frightened by the case of the disappeared Anička, and they are looking for ways to better protect their children.
Also for the price of an impairment of their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about an effective means of reducing the likelihood of tragedy," says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the GPS suppliers on the Czech market.
"I admit that in individual cases there may be misuse of such equipment, for example if you put it in someone's pocket without them knowing about it, but we have not had such a case before."
“Most customers actually buy it for security reasons, ” adds Pilin.
In his opinion, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how to use it in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out, however, that if a child does not like to wear such a thing, he or she simply gets rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to deliberately losing certain things if they do not want to be controlled."
“The mobile phones aroused great expectations among parents at the beginning, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices, ” says Bočková.
They also argue whether such an institution actually helps in the event of an attack.
"In the case of planned kidnappings, the kidnapper practically always checks whether the child has any electronics with which it could be located."
"Today it's the mobile phone."
"If such surveillance devices were to be used more widely, they would also look for them, as their sale would certainly be accompanied by massive advertising."
"In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that similar devices can be helpful in a sudden attack by a paedophile.
According to Roberta Čech from RC Monitoring, which provides locating services for both automobiles and persons, the existence of such a device can help even if it is destroyed immediately after the attack.
"The device can be adjusted in such a way that it reports the respective position at certain intervals."
"Even if it would be destroyed immediately, at least the last position of the person concerned is available."
"In the case of more expensive devices, there is even a built-in inclinometer, which means that if you fall down and remain motionless, the device immediately sends a warning indicating the position," says Mr. Čech.
In his opinion, similar services could also be provided by intelligent mobile phones with navigation, one only has to install special software.
The problem with current tracking devices is that they are either matchbox-sized devices that resemble trailers, or smaller cell phones.
There is always a risk that you will lose them.
According to Mr Pilin of the Macro Weil, we are therefore currently testing equipment that looks like a normal digital watch.
"This has the advantage that the possible attacker does not have to recognize at all that it concerns a monitoring and / or a locating device.
"Or he realizes it only after a certain time, which gives the police a lead in time," he adds.
No matter in which direction the development goes - to wristbands or trailers, always the same technology is used, as with the vehicle location.
In other words, the combination of the GPS ’ s locating function (just like the navigation system in the car) and the function of a mobile phone that reports the current position.
