On the journey through the mangrove swamps crossed by rivers the whole extent of the devastation becomes obvious.
Instead of light water, the motor boat stirs up brown broth; whoever dips his hand into the water pulls out oily fingers.
The roots of the mangrove saplings protrude from the ground like black liquorice sticks, sadly isolated palms let their fronds hang.
Swarms of birds, as they are otherwise common in wetlands, one searches in vain: As soon as the outboard is silent, spreads eerie peace in the former paradise smelling like a gas station.
"What is happening here is ecological warfare," says Celestine Akpobari gloomy: "We live in constant danger to health."
The war comparison is appropriate.
The settlement area of the Ogoni is a battlefield that has been fought over for decades: here the first explorers from Europe invaded more than 60 years ago, here the first resistance organized in the 80s with the later executed writer Ken Saro "Wiwa", here the Shell "corporation had to cease production in 1993 because it became too dangerous for its oil workers.
Even today, the company is unable to return to Ogoniland. While more than two million barrels of black gold are pumped daily from the entire Delta region, which is three times the size of Switzerland, with over 5,000 wells and 7,000 kilometres of pipelines, the oilfields in Ogoniland lie idle, the situation is too unstable for the company.
Every few hundred meters, steel frames protrude out of the water like bizarre sculptures: the heads of the boreholes are called "Christmas trees" far too tenderly.
They are up to 50 years old, most of them corroded to the marrow.
Again and again such a drilling head breaks apart, says Akpobari, then a constant stream of crude oil runs into the water.
According to expert estimates, more than two billion litres have been poured into the Delta ecosystem in 50 years: year after year, the amount of oil that entered the waters off Alaska during the accident of the supertanker "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago - one of the greatest environmental disasters in the history of mankind.
Who is responsible for the persistent ecological meltdown, about it is disputed.
While Shell ’ s corporate corporate sabotage and organized oil theft account for more than 90% of the pollution, environmentalists see bursting drill heads and leaking pipelines as the main causes.
In 2008, the US scientist Richard Steiner accused Shell of setting substantially lower safety standards in Nigeria than is usual in the world: the rate of defects on the pipes alone was "many times higher than elsewhere".
At a place that looks from a distance like an abandoned, oil-smeared workshop under the open sky, figures appear from the mangroves: they are naked and smeared with oil up to their necks.
Under one of the many barrels, which are partly connected with pipes, partly arbitrarily scattered on the area, a fire flickers: an illegal small refinery.
In the barrel, the crude oil is heated over the fire for several hours, explains Michael, the head of the group.
At first gasoline penetrates through the pipes into the collecting pot, later kerosene trickles out at the end of the pipe and finally diesel.
Michael and four employees produce up to four barrels of diesel of 300 litres a day: "That brings us 34,000 naira" - around 22 dollars.
The delta inhabitants use the chronic fuel shortage in the largest oil state in sub-Saharan Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
The illegal cooker can still undercut that with scarcely 40 euro cent per litre ridiculously low Diesel price: Because they get their raw material free of charge.
It comes from "bunkers", which tap the pipeline network across Ogoniland: In this way, the country is lost daily at least 16 Million liters of crude oil, according to experts in the entire Niger Delta.
However, only a tiny fraction of the provisionally intermediate raw material is processed illegally: organised criminal networks, including politicians and high-ranking military personnel, fill the lion ’ s share in tankers and sell it off on the world market.
The activist Akpobari considers purely academic the debate as to whether the environmental catastrophe is due more to the agitation of the population or to the lax mode of production.
"If the oil companies were not perceived as invaders and had not so thoroughly destroyed the livelihoods of the fishermen, there would be no sabotage, theft and illegal refineries."
In the meantime the relationship of the Ogoni above all to Shell is however so destroyed that only a departure of the company would be applicable: “Perhaps other nationalities turn out as better. ”
Michael gets nervous.
"It's high time you disappeared," says the muscular oilman.
"Soldiers can come every minute."
If the illegal oil refiners are caught by the special force of the armed forces, they are not likely to be arrested, but face a painful bribe.
Also the soldiers coming mainly from the country's north - like all Nigerians - want to profit from the raw material.
"This damn stuff has put our country on the dog in every way," says Akpobari.
