Her name appears in documents of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) when it comes to the reactor that Syria allegedly built with the help of North Korea in the rectangular block, hidden in a valley that runs out of electricity.
According to a briefing by the US foreign intelligence agency CIA at the end of April 2008, the reactor, which is also known under the name of the nearby town of El Jabbar, would have been well suited to produce plutonium - from which nuclear weapons could be built.
For other purposes, however, the technology from the fifties is hardly suitable.
The CIA presented a video presentation with blurred satellite images.
Using computer animation, it showed which components of the reactor were supposed to have been before the destruction, which was a scaled down copy of the North Korean model from the Yongbyon nuclear centre.
She also presented photos showing the building up close or even the interior.
The reactor was close to commissioning, it was said, but had not yet been equipped with fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after the bombardment, hardly more is known than at that time, yes, the puzzles became rather bigger with the time.
Former US President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that, while the CIA was fairly certain before the attack that Syria was building a reactor in El Kibar, it saw little evidence that there was "an active nuclear weapons program" in the country.
Some intelligence agencies in Europe prefer to be even more cautious and speak only of an "alleged reactor", even if they consider the CIA presentation to be "plausible".
They lack hard evidence, as does the IAEA.
Asked how safe he was to have a reactor in front of him, a senior UN diplomat replied succinctly in the summer that the IAEA had "enough material to ask questions."
The Syrians hastily removed the rubble from the alleged "unused military building" and thoroughly planned the site.
Nevertheless, in June 2008, an IAEA team led by former chief inspector Olli Heinonen found traces of uranium that had been produced by humans in El Khibar.
Furthermore, the IAEA received, via a Member State, satellite images of commercial operators from the period immediately following the attack, which are likely to be more meaningful than those presented by the CIA.
However, these recordings are not available on the market because the unknown client - perhaps Israel - has bought them exclusively.
The IAEA cannot therefore independently verify its authenticity.
Syria has always maintained that it never operated a secret nuclear program or built a reactor.
Uranium comes from Israeli weapons, Damascus said.
But, after analyzing the particles, the IAEA rejected this as unlikely.
Since then, Damascus has refused to discuss it, as it has about satellite imagery.
It also prevents inspectors from undertaking a second inspection at El Kıbar and access to the ruins of the bombed building.
But Israel, too, remains silent.
"We will never comment," Prime Minister Ehud Olmert, who was in office at the time of the attack, recently confirmed the official position.
Thus, since June 2008, the investigation of the case has been dragging on inconclusively and "is increasingly becoming a serious credibility problem for the Agency", as a senior Western diplomat at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna admits - after all, there is a serious violation of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, which the IAEA oversees.
The IAEA apparently sees three further facilities, which are supposed to be "in functional connection" with the alleged reactor - and which, unlike the latter, still exist - as key to progress in the reconnaissance.
So far, the inspectors have not disclosed which installations they are dealing with, nor what their function is or what makes them appear suspicious.
According to the Süddeutsche Zeitung, they are internally referred to by the IAEA as the Marj as Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah, again derived from nearby cities.
The independent Institute for Science and International Security in Washington (Isis) has identified these locations and used satellite images to locate a building complex near Masyaf, which is most likely one of the suspicious objects.
It may be located in or next to a military base - precisely for this reason, Syria is denying the IAEA access to the three sites.
In Vienna it is said that the Syrians feared a fishing expedition - that the IAEA would be sent forward by the USA to spy on military installations.
Because the nuclear detectives had become aware of the facilities by a tip of the U.S. intelligence agencies.
The IAEA has evidence, including satellite photos, that material has been moved back and forth between the three locations and the cuboid on the Euphrates.
A senior Western diplomat in Vienna said that at least one of the plants could be "related to fuel production."
However, there is "no evidence of sensitive activities", i.e. uranium enrichment or reprocessing; processes that are necessary for the construction of nuclear weapons.
The reactor type is operated with uranium, which is not enriched.
But where the uranium should have come from and where the plutonium for the bomb should later be separated from, these central questions are at best plausible assumptions.
It is also unclear whether debris that could contain valuable traces were stored at the three sites.
As if the hundreds of lorry loads had disappeared from the ground, nobody wants information about where the rubble has gone.
The IAEA considers it unlikely that the Al Tibni salt mine, located just a few kilometres from El Kibar on the other side of the Euphrates River, was tested by Syria in 1998 for its suitability as a radioactive waste storage facility.
Former IAEA Inspector Robert Kelley recently linked it to the reactor in an analysis of satellite imagery for the renowned Jane's Intelligence Review magazine.
However, images from orbit show that Syria was digging at the three suspicious locations and removing large containers after the IAEA had requested access.
This may be a coincidence, but it has done little to dispel the suspicion.
It is also said in diplomatic circles that the IAEA has spent several months on developing a plan for inspections there, which should allow Syria to keep any military secrets - the effort alone shows how great the interest of the inspectors is.
However, Damascus also ironed out this proposal.
A year ago, Western diplomats in Vienna had appeased the idea that the reactor had been destroyed, so the matter was not of great urgency. For example, US Ambassador Glyn Davies has been bringing so-called special inspections into play for a few months, one of the strictest means available to the Vienna Nuclear Safety Agency to enforce inspections.
