These are the findings of the Latinobarómetro, a survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out on a regular basis since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly striking in this year's survey in September and October.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has grown strongly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing at an annual rate of about 6% since 2002, the number of democracy advocates has risen from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has been recovering since last year ’ s sharp slump.
But only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region ’ s most populous countries, are staunch democrats, lowering the regional average (see chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with the democratic practice of their country, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
Approximately 34% trust their country ’ s Congress and 45% their government. Both figures correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America ’ s economic crises undermined efforts to promote democracy.
