The discovery of a foreign bacterial species that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists have discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, in their view it is a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered vital.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"It requires either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"This makes it special, even though it's almost a 'strange' way of life," said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in the online issue of Science on Thursday.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, as the scientists discovered, the bacterium continues to grow in Mono Lake, California, even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"One wonders what else is possible," said the co-author of the report, Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
