This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that in other planetary systems organisms can use other elements to initiate biochemical processes and that the 'standard elements', which we believe are absolutely vital, are not necessarily fixed," said Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a first, because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," Cockell added.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfé Simon of NASA's Astrobiology Institute, which led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically identical, it assumed that microbes exposed to both could possibly replace one element with another.
"The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic works differently from phosphorus. It enters our biochemical system, where it virtually smears everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the GFAJ bacteria to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, the fact that it can survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
According to Jamie S. Foster, professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but there has been no working example.
