Prosecutor Will Not Accuse Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Department of Justice acquitted Senator John Ensign of charges leveled against him following his affair with a former election aide and his attempt to lobby her husband, Senator ’ s lawyers announced on Wednesday.
This decision puts an end to the most serious legal charge against Senator Ensign, the Republican from Nevada. Until the scandal, which made headlines nationwide and put a damper on his career, he was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election.
As Senator Ensign ’ s office announced, he was “delighted ” with the verdict after the one-year investigation.
However, the Senate Ethics Committee could still impose a disciplinary penalty.
According to Ensign ’ s lawyers, they were informed by the Department of Justice that the investigation against Senator Ensign had been stopped and that there were no further charges against him.
The Ministry of Justice did not want to comment on the case.
The ruling came as a surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Justice Department. In their opinion, there was ample evidence that Ensign had violated the lobbying ban.
Interviews, e-mails, and other documents first disclosed in the New York Times in October 2009 gave rise to the suspicion that Ensign helped Douglas Hampton, one of Hampton ’ s election aides, get lucrative contracts to buy his silence over an affair with Hampton ’ s wife, Cynthia.
Cynthia Hampton was Treasurer during an Ensigns election campaign.
Ensign contacted some political friends to get Hampton to work. According to the documents and interrogations, he lobbied for them after Hamptons dismissal.
As Hampton was still in Ensign ’ s recent election team, he was not allowed to lobby his former employer or the entire Senate for a year.
According to ethics experts, the unusual agreement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, violated the so-called revolving door ban.
According to the published evidence, "it appears to be an agreement and a violation of the revolving door statutes," according to Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients targeted by the government.
While the Department of Justice officially refused to disclose the reasons for the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the Department seemed very cautious in taking political charges after a variety of defeats that were followed with great interest by the media, including last year ’ s decision to drop the charges of misconduct against former Senator Ted Stevens.
Prosecutors “are obviously terrible, ” said Melanie Sloan, chairman of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a group of attorneys who have brought various charges against Mr. Ensign to justice.
"This basically means that senior government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, lead counsel for Mr. Ensign, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a public prosecutor on Monday and another phone call the next day, informing him that the ministry would not file charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign ’ s counsel had cooperated with the prosecutors to convince them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law. ”
Mr. Coggins refused to explain in more detail the legal arguments he had put to the prosecutors.
“I ’ m not comfortable going into the details of the conversation between the Ministry of Justice and me. Just this: we think we ’ ve made the right decision, ” he said.
Last month, the Federal Electoral Commission decided to close the investigation into a separate complaint by the Ethics Group alleging that a payment of $96,000 from Mr. Ensign ’ s parents to the Hamptons violated the Federal Elections Act.
The Electoral Commission said that there was not enough evidence that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a large company in Nevada that supported the Senator for a long time, was one of the companies where Mr. Hampton found work with the help of Mr. Ensign lobbyists.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 shows that after Mr. Hampton moved on as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensing's chief of staff, John Lopez, had a conversation with Mr. Hampton in which he told him that he was "knocking" at the Home Office for one thing.
Mr. Ensign was also scheduled for lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after Mr. Hampton hired them to lobby.
When information about the affair first became public last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and abandoned his position in the Senate, where he ranked fourth in the Republican rankings.
After not noticing for many months, Mr. Ensign told reporters two weeks ago that he was seeking a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign is no longer the target of police investigation, his spokesperson, Jennifer Cooper, said the Senator hoped that the Ethics Commission would follow the example of the Department of Justice very quickly and stop its investigation.
"Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work serving the people of Nevada," she said.
Cheshire ’ s Appeal Draws Attention to Twitter
Half a dozen of them typed away in the riots in the courtroom.
Every minute, they sent their reports of gruesome eyewitness testimony via Twitter.
In the end, according to the defense, there were more than 140,000 Twitter reports about the process of rape and bedridden children in a house that went up in flames.
On Thursday, the attentive trial of Steven J. Hayes, accused of killing three members of a family from Cheshire, Connecticut, will come to an official end when the death sentence handed down by the jury is passed.
But Mr. Hayes ’ lawyers have already submitted applications to the court, setting out the grounds for an appeal, which will keep the courts busy for years to come.
One of the most provocative reasons is that intensive reporting on the process - including the extensive use of Twitter by average reporters - had created a "circus atmosphere" and such widespread, immediate penetration of inflammatory details that the jury had been unduly influenced by public outrage.
This objection could lead the courts of appeal to consider whether the new technologies make new rules necessary in the courtroom.
