The presiding judge, Jon C. Blue of the Supreme Court of Appeal, rejected the motions by decision last week, saying that the new media would be "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passions.
But that was certainly not the last word on the matter.
For decades, court appeals have found that reporting on notorious cases casts doubt on the fairness of a trial.
In its historic decision of 1966, the United States Supreme Court overturned the verdict against Dr. Sam Sheppard, an osteopath from Cleveland who is said to have killed his wife, and said in its decision that there had been a "carnival atmosphere in the courtroom" because of the new media.
Some believe that the TV series and the feature film "On the Run" are based on this crime.
Some lawyers say court objections regarding Mr. Hayes ’ conviction half a century later may follow the argument that new rules have become necessary to regulate the channels of communication from the courtroom, which were unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard ’ s case.
