Defendants say they also question the constitutionality of the death penalty constitution, arguing that the judge mistakenly replaced a juror who was a critic of the prosecution, and that he exerted undue pressure on the verdict when he made the unusual decision to release the jury over the weekend.
The jurors were not isolated.
But their arguments about the impact of extensive reporting on the process may attract the greatest interest.
In a court challenge that they filed last month, they found that the case had dominated the news in Connecticut, and was being discussed by candidates during the campaign for the office of governor and the American Senate.
They argued that the new media had continually rekindled the flames of emotion over the case.
“Such a daily rush of media beepers, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom, ” wrote the lawyers,“ has never been seen before in New Haven and perhaps even nationwide. ”
Their focus on Twitter coverage is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists have said that the claim that these direct messages are more inflammatory than reports that are slower is an anti-technology view that impoverishes reporting on future trials.
But some lawyers said that appeal courts are often confronted with the argument that social and technical changes require adaptation by the courts.
