Can courtesy join the divisive?
After a campaign of swearwords and negativity, little courtesy erupted in Washington this week.
Is it the omen of genuine bipartisanship, or a moment of illusion, before quickly returning to the struggle of the parties in the capital?
The meeting on Tuesday between President Obama and the heads of the Congress brought no breakthrough in the big issues that had to be dealt with during the so-called "lame duck session", the meeting at the end of a government period in which no more decisions were made.
According to what one hears, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides nor a consideration of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan scoring.
The public meeting of the President's deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite the political differences that persist between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months creates mutual respect that masks the ideological divide that continues to divide members.
This is hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has dawned.
Both sides are now in a test phase - demanding one from the other sign of cooperation and compromise, while trying to weigh the limits of public opinion and voters' patience after another party war.
Therefore, the meeting on Tuesday itself and its assessment by the participants were limited to a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it is about taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Finally, the November elections in Washington have been lenient for at least a short time.
"No doubt, the tone has changed," said Pete Wehner, an official in the Bush administration who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
"This is inevitable after elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions that die again.
And that is a good thing. "
On some issues, especially those on the lame duck session agenda, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution. "
Bush ’ s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports them.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all, be it temporary or permanent.
Likewise, a compromise on increased unemployment benefits is to be expected, if only because Republicans cannot afford to believe the favored tax cuts for the rich while refusing to support unemployed workers.
Following Tuesday's meeting in the White House, there has been an increase in optimism that agreement can be reached on these issues during the lame duck session, while at the same time ratifying the New START Treaty.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent lame duck issues "need not necessarily lead to lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress is convened in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
"After the things that need to be done are done, this short-term psychology will turn into confrontation," he said.
Wehner is also sceptical - and this scepticism is shared by many - that courtesy leads to true cooperation.
“I see a lot of what will happen from now until 2012 as preliminaries, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012, ” he said.
The reasons for this have much to do with the make-up of the new Republican White House majority and the tea party, which served to educate voters.
Whatever concerns Republican leaders may have about playing too high, they know that they must try to keep their promises to cut government spending and repeal health-care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the deficit commission ’ s recommendations, which include tax reform and raising some taxes, raising the retirement age, and lowering government spending.
Vice-presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes within the Commission to make their plan an official recommendation, and they struggle hard to get anywhere near that number.
The greatest resistance is to be found in the elected representatives of the body, because on financial issues, at least today, there is little room for manoeuvre or little sympathy for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battle between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first fight will take the form of party clashes next year, when Republicans challenge Obama on the state budget, taxes, and health-care systems, followed later by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
Public opinion.
It is proven that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to an impasse, as happened in 1995, both parties must pay careful attention to the public response.
Whoever is condemned to lose will have to change course and seek compromise.
This may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partiality and polarization are larger today than they were in the mid-1990 ’ s, and they seem to be a larger ideological divide between Obama and Congress than between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more far-reaching election in 2012.
In this sense, the courtesy displayed this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a common denominator on the issues that still separate them.
Leaked US document portraying Moscow as a port of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of the "kleptocracy" and it passes on part of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, as reported in February by the American Embassy in Russia in a memo.
Both the police and the State Security Service extort high protection money so that they can maintain their expensive standard of living in Moscow, it is said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organised criminal gangs.
Every layer of bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the 'vertical of authority' - takes its share of the money that moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published on his homepage by WikiLeaks on Tuesday.
The memo is based on sources whose names have been edited.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still Moscow ’ s mayor, and it accused him of corruption.
It was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev, but there is little evidence that it has been cleaned up in the meantime.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a well-known construction company, have consistently rejected accusations of corruption for years, and he has won numerous libel suits against such accusations.
In September, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt, he told a Russian TV station, "It's crazy, it's dirty, it's dirty."
> An incredibly large number of Russians believe that their society is corrupt, according to polls.
But it is unusual, as the Ambassador's report does, for individuals to be named, and it is unheard of that this should be done by a diplomat from a foreign country.
"The direct connection of the Moscow Government with crime has led some to describe it as' disturbed 'and to conclude that the government is acting more like a kleptocrat than a government," the memo said.
"Criminal elements enjoy a" kryshna "(a term from the world of criminals / mafia, which literally means" roof "or protection) that extends across the police, the State Security (FSB), the Service Supervision Authority (MVD) and the Prosecutor's Office, as well as through the entire Moscow government bureaucracy.
Experts have discovered a three-layered structure within the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is at the top of the list."
"FSB, MVD and the militia are on the second level."
"Last, the common criminals and the criminal inspectors follow on the lowest level."
"This is an incompetent system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas because the city offers no help."
The report goes on to say that the FSB collects money from the biggest companies and that the police arrest small businessmen.
One source, it is said, "explained that Moscow's business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and FSB (and not from organized crime) because they have not only more weapons, resources and power than the criminals, but also because they are protected by the law."
"For this reason, protection by criminal gangs is not as much in demand as before."
The memo notes that while the collection of funds is comprehensive, the protection itself is very modest none; even those who pay are sometimes arrested.
Those who do not pay find their business closed very quickly - due to one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about fighting corruption, but at the same time has noted that he has made little progress.
The memo of the embassy contains descriptions of men going to the Kremlin with suitcases that were probably full of money.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev must rely on bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of Indem, a Moscow expert commission, in a recent interview.
"But he is part of this bureaucracy."
"It is not part of the political class, because a political class no longer exists in Russia."
Without politicians, without an opposition, without a separation of powers, he says, corruption is inevitable.
Nationwide, so estimates Indem, corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
The country ranks 154th in a recent survey of the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparence International (countries are listed from "least corrupt" to "most corrupt").
The unveiling of the memo by the American Embassy, which occurred late in the evening after Moscow, will certainly cause displeasure within the Russian government, although, since Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow ’ s mistakes, it may also be a way for the Kremlin to claim that the problems are being solved.
In an interview with Larry King for CNN, Putin claimed that the WikiLeaks documents could be a forgery and reacted angrily to the revelation that American diplomats have named him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth is that it is about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic politics in this country," he said.
“But to be honest, we didn ’ t expect this to happen with such arrogance, with such pressure, and in such an unethical way, you know. ”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront the past
In a dimly lit, concrete classroom with dirty and peeling walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminds us of the man who built him, of the later Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he took care of his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years old.
Known as "the butcher" because of his brutality during the Khmer Rouge reign, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals and bridges, developed infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-time supporters of Anlong Veng are being challenged.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to engage in public confrontation with the people who once supported the regime.
In June, the government distributed a textbook that tells the story of the Khmer Rouge to former soldiers for the first time.
And, in July, a joint UN and Cambodia tribunal first sentenced a former member of the Khmer Rouge to 35 years in prison when it sentenced the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture chamber, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch.
With each of these developments, fear grew among Alnlong Veng ’ s Khmer Rouge veterans, impeding their efforts at reconciliation and reintegration into Cambodian society.
"There is still rejection and fear in the former Khmer Rouge, but they have no power to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia, an independent organisation investigating the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"It even divides families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died of disease, overwork, or starvation.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot Ied government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
Here they spread unrest until December 1998, when the last movement capitulated.
When Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary waged guerrilla warfare from their base in the western mountains and jungles of Cambodia, Ta Mok brought the next generation into Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, when a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country ’ s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to move into government, leading to the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuan Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died a natural death in 1998, and Ta Mok, who did not give in, was arrested by government forces in the Dangrek Mountains in 1999.
He died in 2006 in Phnom Penh Prison, awaiting his trial.
When their patrons no longer protected them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters fled into the grueling poverty of rural Cambodia, and many kept the movement in nostalgic memory.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local government posts because they laid down their weapons, ordinary soldiers remained poor, uneducated peasants.
"These people have benefited very little from the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"They are anchored in the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime."
"They grew up without any professional knowledge."
Sor Lim, 55 years old, who had joined the Rhmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle for Anlang Veng before settling in 1998 to live a life as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone something to eat."
"But now life is hard because we have to take care of ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also raised concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, the Court will try Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, and Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The Court ’ s mandate is to condemn the old leaders and those who are primarily responsible for the atrocities, but it is not said whether it will pursue further acts beyond these four cases.
This has done little to ease the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculations have focused on Im Chaem, 64, who had been district chief in Manteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge ’ s rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told officials at the Documentation Centre of Cambodia that she was leading the construction of the Trapeang Thma Dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are believed to have died.
One hot evening Im Chaem returned from work in the fields to her wooden house on a dirty street outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the withered grass, Im Chaem declined to discuss her past at the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she would refuse to leave, she said.
"Cambodia lives in peace and stability," she said.
"If there were no more persecutions, there would be war here."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who fled the Khmer Rouge in 1878, has also repeatedly warned that the situation would become uncertain if the court charged more suspects, even though experts and historians are discussing this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Centre.
"Reconciliation with the Khmer" means gathering the broken pieces, "he said.
"It is our duty to put these broken parts together so that like everything can understand."
The Centre created the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "History of Democratic Cambodia".
It distributed the book in June in Anlong Veng as an appendix to the High-School History Book of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As is often the case in Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city ’ s links with the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19 years old, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said that the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he brought the book home to read.
"My family rejects many parts of the book and the court," he said.
"They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people will be convicted by the court."
Such resistance makes the reconciliation process complex and complicated, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the schoolbook and the court are gradually gaining influence, "he said.
The Khmer Rouge still has a powerful attraction here.
Up in the Dangrek Mountains, a path overgrown with bushes and dirty with plastic waste leads to a rectangle of black soot covered with a rusty tin roof.
Pol Pot ’ s body was burned here on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31 years old, a mobile phone saleswoman by the roadside, said she didn't know much about the man who had been burned here.
"But he has a strong spirit and many people here go to him to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday and later that day she wanted to go to Pol Pot's last resting place, where she will lay aside a bush of ripe bananas in the hope that it will bring her happiness.
Belarus agrees not to continue accumulating weapons-grade uranium
In a surprising victory for President Obama ’ s campaign to secure nuclear materials worldwide, the Belarusian government announced on Wednesday that it will no longer collect highly enriched uranium, which is a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was announced in a joint statement following a meeting between Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton and Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov in an additional article of the security summit.
The US government had been trying for years to persuade Belarus to stop collecting highly enriched uranium, and seemed to have passed a hurdle last spring.
But US officials told the Washington Post that in the past two months, two secret agreements were made with Belarus to remove 187 pounds of weapons-grade uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
That set the stage for the deal on Wednesday to remove the rest of the material - according to an official employee who remains anonymous due to the sensitivity of the subject, about 500 pounds.
The agreement seems to be one of the most important outcomes of Obama's April "Nuclear Security Summit of 47 Nations", which excluded Belarus.
And it was obviously good enough to secure the invitation of the former Soviet Republic to the next summit in 2012.
“I was really excited about the fact that they want a seat at the Nuclear Security Summit (2012). ”
"This proves to me that it works," said Ken Luongo, President of the Global Security Partnership, a Nuclear Security Group.
Clinton called the agreement "a very important, important step" by Belarus.
Obama promised in Prague in April 2009 to secure all precarious nuclear material within four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries get rid of their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under George W. Bush ’ s administration.
At the time of Obama ’ s nuclear security summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko declared that the nation will never give up its uranium.
"How to keep highly enriched uranium - hundreds of kilos, which is basically weapons-grade, and less enriched uranium," Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material... We won't make dirty bombs of it and we won't sell it to anyone".
"We use it exclusively for research purposes, that's all".
Belarus nevertheless approached the US a few months ago, when it indicated interest in reaching an agreement.
The first attempt to remove uranium of Belarus in October was especially difficult because the material was slightly irradiated, say officials.
It was loaded into a special train, which will take more than 1,300 miles to a Russian factory for storage and disposal, say officials.
The second attempt was decided on Monday and, according to the officials, was carried out by plane.
The U.S. government is paying $14 million for these efforts, with much of the money going to Belarusian research into low-enriched uranium, which cannot be used for nuclear weapons.
“This was extremely carefully coordinated and coordinated to build trust, ” said Andrew Bieniawski, a representative of the Department of Energy working on global risk reduction, which led to the agreement being signed by Clinton.
The James Martin Center for Non-Transfer Studies estimates that Belarus had at least 88 pounds of weapons-grade uranium this year, as well as hundreds of pounds of highly enriched uranium.
