Zapatero and the Red Line of Germany
Berlin opted to keep the euro, but at the same time laid down conditions for the whole of the European Union.
Market tensions have triggered a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, ranging from tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary employment agencies or the abolition of the EUR 426 support for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatisation of 49% of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% of the state lottery.
On the other hand the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of the former governor Felipe González supports the criticism of the chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible person, who had evoked the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is to be anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake of her public relations.
On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
At the same time, Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future, which is clashing with the preservation of the traditional traditions of a large part of its partners.
Faced with resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark - although this currently sounds more like science fiction - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is a restructuring of the euro in line with German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that fail to comply; possible default by some countries; and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits, and the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of the divergence between what Germany deemed necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second signal came from the Central European country, when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to bail out Greece.
This was strongly criticized at the time, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against rescuing Greece.
After all, in the last few days of October, Merkel has come out with a clear position calling for a reform of the European Union ’ s agreements to enable a country to be saved, while at the same time obliging private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position was interpreted as being anti-European, as it drove forward the Irish crisis and everything that followed.
Over the next few months, we will participate in the reform of the European Union, which should make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures now have to be taken, the old way of operating the euro will cease to exist from that date on.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area, in which the offending countries can be severely punished, forced to default, and in which the private sector will have to bear part of the cost.
Germany is showing us that we need to take a tough growth path, with high savings and investment rates, moderation of consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on indebtedness and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as advocated by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It is not just a question of reducing the government deficit to 3% by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will become more calm.
And that we will make use of the opportunities we are offered by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after last Saturday ’ s meeting with the big companies, and yesterday ’ s announcement of new measures) points to the fact that, despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in one ’ s own house has paved the way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look as if anything would change.
One of the possibilities being considered is that we would have to leave the euro area, which is crammed full of unreputable countries.
In that case, Germany could still tell us that it had warned us.
Sport and regulatory evasion
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to evade a sanction.
The exclusion allegedly instigated by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being spilled over whether it was a non-sporting act or not and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will fulfill the prescribed sanction for the next league game against the Auxerre, thus entering the next phase of play without any cards.
Finally, UEFA ’ s disciplinary committee punished the club ’ s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card in such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the debate surrounding the case in question stems from the leading role played by a Real Madrid football team (which pretends to have nobility and honor in its anthem and has punished its players for similar incidents on other occasions), and from the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behaviour, which is expressly forbidden by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a circumvention of the rules. Indeed, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to sportsmanship should be investigated.
The sporting spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not jeopardized by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the offending players take an unjustified advantage of the opposing team. That, too, did not happen.
The paradox of the Real Madrid players' action is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by false play or evasion of rules, because the evasion of the rule was not carried out secretly in order to avoid a sanction, but it should be as noticeable as possible so that it is punished by the referee.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders derived from the intentional fouls.
It should be pointed out here that the rival was neither placed in an unfavorable position nor were advantages required for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue to play with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The obvious advantage is that players can enter the next phase of the Champions League without any cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, to a certain extent uncertain advantage, as the team could eventually be eliminated. In addition, players receive a sanction with this approach and enter the second cycle of cards, in which they are eliminated less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation with a card.
So it is not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
At the end of the day, such practices are not contrary to sportsmanship, which includes making strategic choices to make the most of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to evade a sanction (this would be a definite case of rule evasion), they would rather choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without evading or escaping punishment.
Although the boundary between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic arose as a result of two factors: two self-exclusions and the nature of the provocative transfer of rules.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these acts is less ethical than aesthetic.
