That's where things are. Interpol's 188 countries are instructed to identify and locate Assange "in order to arrest and extradite him provisionally."
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red warning, many member countries, according to the organization, regard the red warning as a carte blanche for arrest - which must be carried out by the national police - especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is likely to be staying.
