China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
At COP16, China ’ s representative said that its country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon emissions, and that it would maintain its offer to cut 40-45% of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China holds its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, affirms Su Wei, the country ’ s representative at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP16), Su Wei asserted that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce carbon emissions and convert its industry.
He said that over the past four years, his country has invested $245 million to reduce greenhouse-gas emissions.
On the other hand, he said that China would not change its objectives, but would work with the international community on this matter.
He explained that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption last year of a new energy law that includes targets for reducing gas emissions, he said.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, the state authorities had worked with the central state and the municipalities to achieve the goals of energy saving, effective use of energy, and reduction of emissions.
He also pointed out that some multi-annual plans have already been started or completed, both those financed by the Chinese Government and those that have received funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the programme for the effective use of energy, which was introduced in the last five years and received investment from the United Nations (UN), the government and private investors.
There is also a provincial project on climate change, another on replacing traditional light bulbs with energy-saving ones, and another on mitigation and adaptation, he said.
Martin Krol, China ’ s scientific adviser on climate change, confirmed that China ’ s efforts are far greater than is commonly believed.
He pointed out that per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China are six tonnes per person, while in the United States they are 100 tonnes. China is responsible for a 9% total contribution to pollution.
It is also making unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has increased by twenty percent in the last five years and is set to increase by 2020, he said.
