She leaves the infectologist convinced: "Patience is not my strength, perhaps that is my wound."
Finally, after a frustrating approach to the traumatologist, who took her breath away in the middle of the corridor and explained to her that wound is not a scientific concept, the psychoanalyst reveals the secret: "the wound is the really open, the symbolic is the scar."
The main character of the story sighs with relief and concludes that she "only learned from the wound that it was really open and did not exist." But she is convinced that the pleasure of language and its traps mix.
Valenzuela, the writer, played with both.
The Nicaraguan Sergio Ramírez also presented a delightful tale, which he called 'Praise of the Invention', in which the finger in the wound is not mentioned, but discovered.
With allusions to magical realism, he tells of a famous sorceress who touched the clouds, brought back men who had traveled far away, or restored the virtue lost by a girl. It made a U-turn and told of America, the great novel that did not lack its own chronicler from the beginning, and he quoted Bernal Díaz del Castillo, who criticized the abundance of stories told by the conquerors.
"Cervantes, who invited all of us (the writers), mocked the pretended witnesses who appeared in the stories portrayed as true, but otherwise the story of America would never have been told - with imagination, which even lost its sense of shame."
However, he emphasizes that "it is the madmen and liars who imagine things the best," and that is where reality and lies approach each other, where one no longer knows to which side the story belongs, where fictional literature reaches its climax.
He actually calls this the 'Cervantes Tradition'.
"From him we have inherited to be what is told."
When it was Mayra Montero's turn, the writer commented and praised the variety of interpretations to which FIl's invitation to the round table 'The finger in the wound' had contributed.
The Cuban and Puerto Rican woman dedicated her contribution to the great wound of social violence that afflicts her country - like all of Latin America - as a result of the struggles for drug trafficking.
"I believe that good literature, good poetry, good songs, contain a tacit, not purposely planned engagement," she said after emphasizing that literature is communication and commitment that builds up between the author and the reader as if in a "chemical reaction."
The evening was concluded by the Spanish poet Luis García Montero, whose contribution also highlighted "this finger of the committed writer in the writer's wound".
He noted that in a fast-paced world, intellectual habits and the control of consciousness also boil down to dogmatism, and he forgets "that behind every affirmation is a little no, and behind every denial a little yes."
"To be in possession of our thoughts and of reality, we have to nuance: and nuancing often means putting one's finger in the wound and harassing those who feel much more comfortable when thinking in the form of caricatures, in black and white, in prefabricated ideas without nuances, and also harassing the powerful who prefer to divide the world into black and white, he noted, inviting them to rediscover the meaning of writing.
