The US changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Persons are required to present themselves at the visa application services at the consulate before their interview, thus reducing waiting times.
From 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for visas at the United States Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will have to present themselves to the visa application services (ASC, the initial letters in English) before going to the consulate.
The ASC staff collects the biometric data of the applicant, which are checked by the consulate before the interview.
The new process has certain advantages for aspirants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa decreases, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately for arranging the appointment, processing the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant makes only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and 390 dollars for traders and investors.
Those who just want to extend their visa do not have to talk to the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
As the biometric data are collected at the ASC, applicants needing a second appointment at the consulate will have less time than before.
Those who apply for a visa at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will not have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, please visit: http: / / mexico.usembassy.gov / boletines / sp101201 _ Visa ’ s FAQs.html
