Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in the greenhouse gas (CFCs), which is almost a third of the additional reduction that must be achieved in order to stabilise the earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its place in the concrete large-scale projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments from developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of CFC emitted by means of lighting, if the incandescent bulbs, which currently constitute a 50 to 70% monopoly on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or, better still, by light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
Lighting accounts for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust emissions of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, major exhaust emitters such as the United States, China, Europe, and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans aimed at reducing global CFCs emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, another 5 Gt would have to be deducted from this balance sheet in order to stabilise the 2 ° C rise in the climate between now and 2020 in order to prevent it from spiralling out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs escapes 95% of the energy in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with the new LEDs, light bulbs can be reduced by twice as much.
The compact fluorescent bulbs last between 6000 to 10,000 hours on average.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the Philips manufacturer this week - which incidentally participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, indicating the savings potential of the replacement plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that these completely new types of light bulbs emit very little heat, they can also work with a regulating resistor.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves because they contain mercury and that they must therefore be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless producers provide a collection point.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but rather the coal-fired power stations, which emit far more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power stations emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury annually.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make from this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save $1 billion annually on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 coal-fired power plants, which Indonesia would cost 2.5 billion to build.
