Vengeful hackers and busy spies
The WikiLeaks Affaire has a dual meaning.
On one side, it has turned out to be an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal of hypocrisy in the sense that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and gives a foretaste of the regression-dominated future.
But let us proceed one by one.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that every file produced by a secret service (an arbitrary nation x) is composed exclusively of newspaper clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits are nothing more than what has been read for months in every journal (except for those owned by Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's shockingly caricatured profile has long provided cabaret artists with material for their sketches.
The rule according to which secret files can only consist of news that is already known is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not just this century.
If you go to a library dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes, le Chateau, the Templars, or the Rosaries) repeats exactly what was written in previous works.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the non-existing), but because those who devote themselves to occultism do not believe in anything other than what they already know and confirm what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown's mechanism of success.
Likewise the Secret Files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) is also the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be anything, for example editor at Libération), who only considers what he recognizes to be true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as the one that Newsweek had published the week before.
So why has such a fuss been made about the disclosures of these dossiers?
On one side, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War and since then also the Heads of Government can call each other or take an aeroplane to meet for dinner - have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small representational tasks, have turned into espionage centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that this is being done to ignore it.
Nevertheless, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the abandonment of hypocrisy and serves to cast American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that any hacker can tap into the most secret secrets of the world ’ s most powerful country has a major impact on the state department ’ s prestige.
Furthermore, the scandal is bringing distress not so much to the victims as to the 'executioners'.
But let us look at the profound nature of what happened.
Formerly, in Orwell ’ s time, all power could be pooled like a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Since then, Orwell ’ s prophecy could have turned out to be completely correct, where every movement can be controlled thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the motorway chosen and so on; the citizen would become the total victim of the eye of power.
But if we consider what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the control corridor ceases to be one-sided and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen as the avenger of the citizen - can discover the secrets of power.
But how can a power keep itself that is no longer able to keep its own secrets?
True, Georg Simmel has already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of Berlusconi ’ s or Merkel ’ s character is basically a secret free of secrets, since it exposes the public sphere; but to reveal, in the style of WikiLeaks, that Hillary Clinton ’ s secrets were empty secrets is to deprive them of any power.
WikiLeaks has done neither Sarkozy nor Merkel wrong, but Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult inflicted on such a vast power?
It is obvious that the states will no longer put any reserved information online in the future - this would be tantamount to a poster stuck on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies, it is in vain to hope to keep confidential reports over the phone secret.
Nothing is easier than to find out whether and when a head of state has moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships be maintained in the future, and only for certain ears?
I know very well that my prediction at the moment sounds like science fiction and novelistic, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents, secretly busily moving along uncontrollable routes, carrying their messages nowhere but in memory, and furthermore hiding the little written information they have received in the heel of their shoes.
The information would be stored in single copies in closed drawers: basically, Watergate ’ s espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now progressing like a cancer, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communication, the Internet reconstructs a telegraph with (telephone) wire.
The (analog) video cassettes had enabled the film researchers to explore a film tape by tape, by being able to wind from the back to the front and reveal all the secrets of the montage, while the (numerical) CDs nowadays allow nothing else but to jump from chapter to chapter, in macroportions.
The high-speed trains run from Rome to Milan within three hours, while it takes three and a half hours by plane, including the transfer.
It is therefore not unusual for politics and communication technology to return to the car and horse.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between the messages.
At the moment, it is the embassies that demand confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France improves its financial promises
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine the implementation of the fast-start financing commitments made by developing countries.
And already the coarse French beautifications are revealed.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, developing countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years, France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to convince its partners of its commitment to Fast Start funding: detailed process report from its Member States, press conference, major side events, brochure distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and precisely appreciated for its intrinsic value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same thing at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to respect its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But if you look at the details, things are a little more complicated.
This money should, according to the Copenhagen Treaty, be 'new and additional' in order to ensure that an additional effort was made without being to the detriment of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what 'new and additional' means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonization, certain member states, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark he considers best.
For example, the EU ’ s Commission has chosen as a benchmark for 2009: international funding will be maintained, adding €150 million over three years under Fast Start funding.
Other countries have adopted similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of Official Development Assistance.
In return, France considered that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional".
In other words, there are no benchmarks for spending in the previous year or at the global level of official development assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French assistance to developing countries can remain stable (or decrease) - France claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule about this yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, include 1 borrowed €as equivalent to 1 donated €.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans for certain profitable investments (projects often linked to mitigation, based on the most effective technology) can be justified, it is deceptive to present the euro that one collects as the equivalent of a donated euro... Moreover, only the cost of the loan to the donor country should be credited as commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing else in mind than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking out 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5%) (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU-document to see for yourself.
France is the only EU country that makes significant use of loans.
Germany is asking for 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are fulfilling their obligations 100% with donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet its commitments, France gives just 10 cents, which is a similar commitment.
Beautiful hocus-pocus!
All in all, in its Fast Start, France operates with a double swindle: on the one hand with a further development of the action over time and on the other hand with the reality of the financial effort.
France manages to make believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" million in accordance with its promises, saving EUR 36.1 million.
The manipulation of the Treasury (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; on the one hand, the EU (why do the other member states continue with the donation, if it is enough to borrow?) and on the other hand, in the negotiations, since the developing countries cannot be completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing is only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the totality of discussions on climate.
But it could be too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
Be that as it may, it is imperative to learn his lesson from this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and compensatory justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could advance the debate on the issue of long-term financing (another, crucial, and currently debated issue): it does not escape the question of “accountability ” or the accounting nature of its loans.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister, Kosciusko Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about France ’ s Fast Start and its vision of “accountability ” and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base needed for further discussion.
